On 02/04/2019 01:29 PM, Noel Chiappa wrote:
> Does one name (in the generic high-level sense of the term 'name';=20
> e.g. an 'address' is a name for a unit of main memory) apply to the nod=
e=20
> (host) no matter how many interfaces it has, or where it is/moves in=20
> the network? If so, that name names the node. If not...

The vagaries of multi-homed hosts make the answer more complicated.

I generally think that a host name applies to the host, no matter how=20
many interfaces it has, or where it is / moves in the network.  But=20
that's the "host name".

There are other names, like service names, that apply to a service and=20
can (re)pointed to any desired back end host name at any given time.

I usually think that host names should resolve to all IPs that are bound =

to a host.  I then rely on the DNS server to apply some optimization=20
when possible about which IP is returned first based on the client's IP. =

  I also depend on clients preferring IPs in the directly attached=20
network segment(s).

> No. Multi-homed hosts in IPv4 had multiple addresses. (There are all so=
rts=20
> of kludges out there now, e.g. a single IP address shared by a pool of =

> servers, precisely because the set of entity classes in IPvN - hosts,=20
> interfaces, etc - and namespaces for them were not rich enough for the =

> things that people actually wanted to do - e.g. have a pool of servers.=
)

Please allow me to clarify.

First, I'm excluding load balancers or similar techniques that spread an =

IP out across multiple back end servers.  Save for saying that I'd argue =

that such an IP belongs to the load balancer, not the back end server.=20
That aside.

Multi-homed IPv4 hosts (all that I've tested) usually allow traffic to a =

local IP to come in on any interface, even if it's not the interface=20
that the IPv4 address is bound to.

Take the following host:

+---+   +-----------------+   +---+
| A +---+ eth0   B   eth1 +---+ C |
+---+   +-----------------+   +---+

Even if B has IPv4 forwarding disabled, A will very likely be able to=20
talk to B via the IPv4 address bound to eth1.  Likewise C can talk to B=20
using the IPv4 address bound to eth0.

My understanding is that IPv6 changes this paredigm to be explicitly the =

opposite.  If B has IPv6 forwarding disabled, A can't talk to B via the=20
IPv6 address bound to eth1.  Nor can C talk to B via the IPv6 address=20
bound to eth0.

That's why I was saying that the IPv4 addresses on eth0 and eth1=20
belonged to the OS running on B, not the specific interfaces.

> Ignore what term(s) anyone uses, and apply the 'quack/walk' test -=20
> how is it used, and what can it do?

I will have to test this when time permits.

But the above matches how I remember the duck quacking and walking.

> Names (in the generic sense above) used by the path selection mechanism=
=20
> (routing protocols do path selection).
>=20
> They aren't. But the path selection system can't aggregate information =

> (e.g.  routes) about multiple connected entities into a single item (to=
=20
> make the path selection scale, in a large network like the Internet)=20
> if the names the path selection system uses for them (i.e. addresses,=20
> NSAP's, whatever) are allocated by several different naming authorities=
,=20
> and thus bear no relationship to one another.
>=20
> E.g. if my house's street address is 123 North Street, and the house ne=
xt=20
> door's address is 456 South Street, and 124 North Street is on the othe=
r=20
> side of town, maps (i.e. the data used by a path selection algorithm to=
=20
> decide how to get from A to B in the road network) aren't going to be=20
> very compact.

Agreed.  The number of routes / prefixes and the paths to get to them=20
has been exploding for quite a while now.  I think the IPv4 Default Free =

Zone is approaching 800,000 routes / paths.



--=20
Grant. . . .
